From dawagner David Wagner Subject Re viewing postscript files under X windows In article Kin Cho writes I can also live with a utility that converts postscript to plain text perferably retaining page counts so that I know how many pages the original document Well I know of one hack to sort of do this First get ghostscript and check out the gs file that comes with It prints out some information about where each text string goes on the page and maintains page I've written a little C program to massage the output of gs dNODISPLAY gs somewhat so that you can get all the ascii strings in the No guarantees that it won't break up words sentences though I've used it with varying degrees of Anyways try this out it may do what you massager a filter for use with gs does crude Postscript ASCII conversion Usage cat gs dNODISPLAY gs massager I print a Ctrl L after each new Put the following source into and compile it include include main char line p while fgets line sizeof line stdin NULL if line 'P' printf f n else if line 'S' line ' ' if p strrchr line ' ' NULL continue p ' ' if p strchr line ' ' NULL continue for p p p if p ' ' p ' ' p ' ' putchar p putchar ' n' return David Wagner